%I A397689 #23 Jul 13 2026 22:07:46
%S A397689 2,17,19,5,7,13,11,13,19,31,3,5,11,23,43,73
%N A397689 Irregular triangle read by rows: let p be the least prime such that k*(k + 1)*(k + 2)/3 + p produces primes for k=0..n-1 and a composite for k=n, the n-th row gives the list of primes for k=0..n-1.
%C A397689 This sequence is finite, and the triangle has only six rows, of which the fifth is empty.
%C A397689 Proof: (Start)
%C A397689 Let T(k) = k*(k + 1)*(k + 2)/3, it is sufficient to prove that there does not exist a prime p such that T(k) + p produces primes for k=0..n-1 and a composite for k=n for n != 1, 2, 3, 4, and 6. Firstly, we observe that T(k) mod 3 is periodic with period 9. In fact, k + 9 == k (mod 9) implies that (k + 9)*(k + 10)*(k + 11) == k*(k + 1)*(k + 2) (mod 9). Hence, T(k+9) == T(k) (mod 3) after division by 3. Since T(0) + p = p is always a prime and every prime falls into one of the three residue classes modulo 3, we have the following three cases:
%C A397689 * If p == 1 (mod 3), we obtain that T(1) + p = 2 + p == 0 (mod 3). Thus, T(1) + p is composite for k=1, which corresponds to the case n = 1.
%C A397689 * If p == 2 (mod 3), we get that T(1) + p = 2 + p == 1 (mod 3), T(2) + p = 8 + p == 1 (mod 3), T(3) + p = 20 + p == 1 (mod 3), and T(4) + p = 40 + p == 0 (mod 3). This implies that the length of the prime runs could not exceed 4. Such cases correspond to the values of n in {1, 2, 3, 4} and to their respective least primes 2, 17, 5, and 11.
%C A397689 * If p = 3, the direct computation of T(k) + 3 for k=0..5 yields 3, 5, 11, 23, 43, 73, which are all primes. However, T(6) + 3 = 115 = 112 + 3 = 115 = 5*23, which is composite. This yields a run of length n = 6.
%C A397689 Lastly, since every prime in the three residue classes provides runs of length equal to either exactly 1, or at most 4, or exactly 6, it is possible to conclude that the admissible values of n are in {1, 2, 3, 4, 6}. QED. (End)
%e A397689 The irregular triangle:
%e A397689   { 2};
%e A397689   {17, 19};
%e A397689   { 5,  7, 13};
%e A397689   {11, 13, 19, 31};
%e A397689   {};
%e A397689   { 3,  5, 11, 23, 43, 73}.
%t A397689 row[n_]:=Module[{k=1}, While[!(AllTrue[list=Table[m(m+1)(m+2)/3+Prime[k], {m, 0, n-1}], PrimeQ] && !PrimeQ[n(n+1)(n+2)/3+Prime[k]]), k++]; list]; Flatten@Join[Array[row, 4],row[6]]
%Y A397689 Cf. A002378 (first differences of k*(k + 1)*(k + 2)/3), A002476, A003627, A164926.
%K A397689 nonn,fini,full,tabf,new
%O A397689 1,1
%A A397689 _Stefano Spezia_, Jul 05 2026
